Update your Spring Boot application to allow requests from the React application's domain. You can do this by adding the `@CrossOrigin` annotation to your controller or by configuring CORS in your application. Here's an example using `@CrossOrigin`:
_@RestController_
_@RequestMapping("/api")_
_@CrossOrigin(origins = "<http://localhost:3000>") // Replace with your React app's URL_
_public class YourController {_
    _// Your controller code here_
_}_
In your React application, when making API calls, ensure that you specify the full URL, including the port number. You can use the `fetch` function or libraries like Axios to make HTTP requests. Here's an example using `fetch`:
_fetch('<http://localhost:8080/api/your-endpoint>')_
    _.then(response => response.json())_
    _.then(data => console.log(data))_
    _.catch(error => console.error('Error:', error));_
If you don't want to deal with CORS during development, you can use a proxy setup. In your React application's `package.json` file, you can add a `proxy` field:
_"proxy": "<http://localhost:8080>",_
